 font-weight:bold">xecutive summary</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government education reforms, aimed at improving school standards, have led to a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n increasingly autonomous schools system, through conversion of existing schools to Academy status and opening of new schools as Free Schools. These schools have greater freedoms in a variety of areas including whether to expand school places to meet deman</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d, decide self-improvement needs and are their own admissions authority.   </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These reforms have directly led to a decline of the traditional council role in educ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ation. Yet, government is clear; local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as champions of children and parents, with a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">democratic mandate, have a responsibility that every school do their best for the local population. Local authorities continue to hold legal duties covering education including to ensure sufficient school places, overall responsibility for school performan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce in the local area and fair access for all children.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since 2010, schools that have converted to Academy status have risen from 38 to 185 at secondary level and from 0 to 125 at primary level in the capital. At the same time, more Free Schools have been s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">et up in London than in any other part of England. Of the 174 Free Schools opened in England, a total of 58 (34 per cent) are in London. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a greater proportion of London’s schools convert to Academy status and further Free Schools are set up, the D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">epartm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ducation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will be unable to work with or provide the necessary support needed by each school. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Based on evidence from across London, London Councils has identified gaps </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">within system that put at risk the aspirations behind government reforms. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local government has a vital role to play in ensuring continued improvement to the schools system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> following </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">five </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">changes are needed to support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">autonomous schools flourish whilst</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at the same time providing parents with the reassurance needed within the education system:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 70.9pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-42.55pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> support schools address signs of failure at the earliest opportunity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> - Local authority issued early warning notices for Academies and Free Schools should be sup</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ported by a statutory backstop, in the same way they are for maintained schools.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 70.9pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-42.55pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To ensure new schools are setup in areas/wards where there is projected demand - A change in government policy to put new school applicants in touch with London boroughs at th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e earliest chance.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.9pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-42.55pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To support vulnerable children – Government should provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Fair Access Panels with the power to issue a direction to an Academy to admit a hard-to-place pupil, as they currently do with maintained schools </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.9pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-42.55pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Making the education system more accessible to parents and local communities - Ensuring Academies share the same statistical returns with local authorities at the same time they make them available </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to the Department for Education. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 70.9pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-42.55pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iving local authorities the powers to order a financial audit or investigation for Academies, as they can currently with maintained schools. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">GENERAL</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, including working with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sponsors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local authorities are legally responsible for providing school places for every child resident in their area. To do this, boroughs closely monitor the supply and demand for places and ensure there is sufficient school capacity to meet the needs o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f their community.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All regions are experiencing a rise in demand for school places but this a pressure not spread evenly across the country. Over the 10</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> since Census 2001, London’s population grew by 900,000 (11.6 per cent). </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London Councils latest </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">analysis has shown that between 2012/13 and 2016, the shortage of school places is set to reach 118</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,000. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For many local authorities, it is becoming increasingly challenging to create additional classrooms in existing schools. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ocal authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o longer h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ave the sole responsibility for commissioning new school places in a local area. Existing a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cademies, of which there are 368</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in London, are responsible for their own expansion and should they opt to do so, bid directly to the Department for Education for fu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nding. The Government also approves applications for new Free Schools without consultation with local authorities. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Within boroughs and across London, like all reg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ions, engagement with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> academies to expand and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> liaison with Free School applicants</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> before they</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> submit a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bid </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to government vary significantly. There is no systematic approach in place and many local authorities only find out about plans to expand or create new Free Schools once they have been approved by Government. This makes it difficult for local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> authorities to be able to include these new places in medium to long term place planning. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In particular, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s recently highlight</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed by the National Audit Office</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Establishing Free Schools,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a number of Free Schools approved by the government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are set up</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in temporary premises, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">failed to open</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or are not in wards/areas of projected demand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> made it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">extremely difficult to coordinate admissions as parents may select</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a school that does not open, cannot accommodate their child or is no in an area of pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">jected demand.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other organisations operating between the Secretary of State and individual schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and what gaps there are in su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">pport for schools at this level?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local authorities have 198 statutory duties relating to education and children and young people's services to discharge. Irrespective of school provider type, local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">authorities have three core </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">responsibilities in relation to education - ensuring a sufficient supply of school places, tackling underperformance in schools and ensuring high standards as well as supporting vulnerable children. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a more</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> autonomous education system has evolved, it has become increasingly challenging for local authorities to discharge these duties. At the same time, central government’s ability to support academies and free schools will become progressively strained as the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">number of Academies and Free Schools increases</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local authorities, as champions of children and parents, with a democratic mandate, have a responsibility that every school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> do their best for the local population and therefore, ensure the aspiratio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ns behind government reforms are fulfilled. Based on evidence from across London, London Councils has identified five key changes that are needed to address risks in the system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Enabling continued school improvement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Academies and Free Schools are respons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ible for their own school improvement as outlined in the Education Act 2011. However, some schools will not be able to thrive on their own and DfE and Ofsted do not have the capacity to work with each school in the country to prevent standards declining. I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t is critical that support and challenge is offered to schools at the earliest possible moment to minimise the impact that any signs of failure may have on the quality of education a child receives.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London boroughs are well placed to do this and have succ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">essfully demonstrated how they use early warning notices, when serious issues emerge, to turn around performance in maintained schools.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London Councils is calling on government to enable local authorities to issue early warning notices to all state funded </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">schools, supported by a statutory backstop, to ensure that they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> upon by schools, irrespective of type to prevent failure.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Meeting the growing demand for school places</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Many Academies and Free Schools work closely with local authorities and consult them on the potential to expand or set up new schools. However, there is no systematic approach in place and many local authorities only find out about plans to expand or crea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">te new schools once they have been approved by the government. In some instances in London, Academies and Free Schools have opened in areas where there is limited demand for schools and therefore, take up of places is extremely low by local families. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">address these inconsistencies within the system, London Councils believes there is a strong role for local authorities, with their expert local knowledge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and intelligence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, to offer a package of support to Academies and Free Schools. This could include effe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ctive advice on viable sites and development costs; and ensuring schools sufficiently meet community needs. This would enable local authorities to broker effective relationships with Free School candidates and support those that demonstrate quality, cost-e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ffectiveness and meet the growing need for places.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In order for this to be effective and deliver parental choice in state education, London Councils is calling on government to share information on Free School candidates </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at the earliest opportunity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Supp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">orting vulnerable children to achieve positive outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Supporting vulnerable children to achieve positive outcomes is an integral part of a local authority’s duties. It is important that the education reforms do not hinder a borough’s ability to fulfil th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ese duties, particularly in relation to schools. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Placing excluded pupils in appropriate schooling is a particularly difficult duty to deliver and every part of the school system needs to share equally in this responsibility. To ensure the system is viabl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e in a world with a majority of Academies, government needs to act to empower Fair Access Panels to issue a direction to an Academy to admit a hard-to-place pupil, as they currently do with maintained schools.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Making the education system more accessible t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">o parents and local communities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In an autonomous schools sector driven by choice parents will play an increasingly important role in shaping local education provision. However, many parents will need support in order to make informed decisions as they navi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gate their way through the market. It will be increasingly difficult for parents to locate, understand and compare data for all schools as the market diversifies. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London Councils is calling on all schools, including academies, to share the same data and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">statistical returns with local authorities at the same time that they make them available to the DfE. Local authorities can then make this data available to local parents and also use it to support the local family of schools, challenging those where issue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s are emerging, and enabling the more effective delivery of their statutory duties.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-28.35pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local authorities should be able to conduct a financial audit or investigation into any school, including Academies, if they feel that there are issues deserv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing further scrutiny. This information would be important for the wider community to be able to assess the value for money provided by a school.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">4</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>